summary: Joaquin S. Roman, 31, went on a rampage culminating at a Kum & Go, killing four people, including a police officer, before fatally shooting himself on the scene.

Anthony Ferrill, 51, an employee armed with two handguns, including one with a silencer, opened fire on the Milwaukee campus of the beer company, killing five people and then committing suicide. According to the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, Ferrill "had been involved in a long-running dispute with a co-worker that boiled over" in the run-up to the attack.

David N. Anderson, 47, and Francine Graham, 50, were heavily armed and traveling in a white van when they first killed a police officer in a cemetery, and then opened fire at a kosher market, “fueled both by anti-Semitism and anti-law enforcement beliefs,” according to New Jersey authorities. The pair, linked to the antisemitic ideology of the Black Hebrew Israelites extremist group, were killed after a lenghty gun battle with police at the market.

Ahmed Mohammed al-Shamrani, A Saudi Arabian military pilot training in the United States, opened fire just before 7 a.m. in an air station classroom. He was soon shot and killed by responding Florida sheriff’s deputies.

Seth A. Ator, 36, fired at police officers who stopped him for a traffic violation, and then went on a driving rampage in the Odessa-Midland region, where he also shot a postal worker and stole her vehicle. He was shot dead by law enforcement responding to the rampage. Ator had been fired from a job just prior to the attack (though per the FBI he had shown up to that job "already enraged"). He had a criminal record and "a long history of mental problems and making racist comments," according to a family friend who spoke to the media.
mental_health_details: "One friend of the family said the gunman had a long history of mental problems, trouble with the law and making racist comments," according to a report in the New York Times.

summary: Connor Betts, 24, died during the attack, following a swift police response. He wore tactical gear including body armor and hearing protection, and had an ammunition device capable of holding 100 rounds. Betts had a history of threatening behavior dating back to high school, including reportedly having hit lists targeting classmates for rape and murder.
weapon_details: AR-15-style rifle, with a 100-round capacity ammunition drum

summary: Patrick Crusius, 21, who was apprehended by police, posted a so-called manifesto online shortly before the attack espousing ideas of violent white nationalism and hatred of immigrants. "This attack is a response to the Hispanic invasion of Texas," he allegedly wrote in the document.

Santino William LeGan, 19, fired indiscriminately into the crowd near a concert stage at the festival. He used an AK-47-style rifle, purchased legally in Nevada three weeks earlier. After apparently pausing to reload, he fired additional multiple rounds before police shot him and then he killed himself. A witness described overhearing someone shout at LeGan, "Why are you doing this?" LeGan, who wore camouflage and tactical gear, replied: “Because I'm really angry." The murdered victims included a 13-year-old girl, a man in his 20s, and six-year-old Stephen Romero.

DeWayne Craddock, 40, a municipal city worker wielding handguns, a suppressor and high-capacity magazines, killed en masse inside a Virginia Beach muncipal building late in the day on a Friday, before dying in a prolonged gun battle with police. Craddock reportedly had submitted his resignation from his job that morning. He was a veteran of the Virginia Army National Guard, and "had a shaved head, bodybuilder’s physique and cameras in the windows of his house on a peaceful cul-de-sac," according to the Washington Post.
weapon_details: .45-caliber handguns; noise suppressor (silencer); several high-capacity magazines

summary: Gary Martin, 45, went on a rampage inside the warehouse in response to being fired from his job and died soon thereafter in a shootout with police. Among his victims were five dead coworkers and five injured police officers. Martin had a felony record and lengthy history of domestic violence; he was able to obtain a gun despite having had his Illinois firearms ownership identification card revoked. According to a report from prosecutors, Martin told a co-worker the morning of the shooting that if he was fired he was going to kill employees and police.
weapon_details: Smith & Wesson handgun, with a green sighting laser

summary: Jordan Witmer, 21, shot three people at a Ramada Hotel bar near Penn State University, including a former girlfriend he was there with. He then fled the bar, crashed his car about a mile away, and stormed into a random house, fatally shooting an elderly resident and then himself. Witmer, who had a legal carry permit for his handgun, had just finished a three-year stint in the US Army; ten days prior to the attack he had been convicted on drunk driving-related charges in Kentucky, where he'd been stationed.

Zephen A. Xaver, 21, fatally shot five women inside a bank and then called the police to confess. He was armed with a handgun and wore a bulletproof vest. He reportedly ordered the women to lie down on the floor and shot them execution-style. After a standoff with police, he surrendered and was taken into custody. A week prior, Xaver had quit a job as a prison guard trainee, and authorities said they believed the shooting was "a random act" and that roberry did not appear to be a motive. An ex-girlfriend in Indiana told local media she'd been “scared for years” by Xaver’s talk of violence and death, but that her warnings to others (who she did not identify) were not taken seriously. She said she’d first met Xaver in a psychiatric hospital in 2013. In March 2017, Michigan State Police documented an incident in which Xaver indicated he was “possibly thinking of suicide by cop and taking hostages."
mental_health_details: Xaver was reported to have a lenghty history of expressing violent desires; an ex-girlfriend said she first met him at a psychiatric hospital in 2013.

summary: Ian David Long, 28, dressed in black and armed with a handgun and a “smoke device,” approached the Borderline Bar & Grill — a country music venue popular with college students — close to midnight and opened fire, killing a security guard and then others in the club, including a sheriff’s deputy responding to the attack. Long was found dead at the scene from apparent suicide. He was a former Marine and had a history of interactions with local law enforcement, including a mental health evaluation in which he’d been cleared.
mental_health_details: Per the LATimes: "Sheriff Geoff Dean said his department had had several interactions with Long, including a call to his home in April for a complaint of disturbing the peace. Deputies at the time said Long was irate and acting irrationally, Dean said. They called in mental health professionals to evaluate him, and they concluded he did not need to be taken into custody."
where_obtained: A gun store in Simi Valley

summary: Robert D. Bowers, 46, shouted anti-Semitic slurs as he opened fire inside the Tree of Life synagogue during Saturday morning worship. He was armed with an assault rifle and multiple handguns and was apprehended after a standoff with police. His social media accounts contained virulent anti-Semitic content, and references to migrant caravan "invaders" hyped by President Trump and the Republican party ahead of the 2018 midterms elections.
where_obtained: (Unclear; investigators confirmed he owned 10 guns in total, all purchased and possessed legally, and had a handgun license)

summary: Snochia Moseley, 26, reportedly a disgruntled employee, shot her victims outside the building and on the warehouse floor; she later died from a self-inflicted gunshot at a nearby hospital. (No law enforcement officers responding to her attack fired shots.)

Javier Casarez, 54, who was going through a bitter divorce, went on a shooting spree targeting his ex-wife and former coworkers at the trucking company. His attack included fatally shooting one victim who he pursued to a nearby sporting goods retailer, and two others at a private residence. After then carjacking a woman who was driving with a child (and letting the two go), Casarez fatally shot himself as law enforcement officials closed in on him.

Omar Enrique Santa Perez, 29, walked into the ground-floor lobby of a building in downtown Cincinnati shortly after 9 a.m. and opened fire. Within minutes, Perez was fatally wounded in a shootout with law enforcement officers responding to the scene.
mental_health_details: Perez filed a "delusional" lawsuit in 2017 against CNBC and TD Ameritrade; the federal judge who threw out the case said Perez's allegations were "rambling, difficult to decpipher and borders on delusional."

summary: Jarrod W. Ramos, 38, shot through the glass doors of the paper’s newsroom around 3pm to carry out his attack; police quickly responding to the scene found him hiding under a desk and apprehended him. Ramos had harbored a longstanding grudge against the paper over a 2011 column that had detailed his guilty plea for the harassment of a former female classmate. Ramos had sued the paper for defamation and lost.

Dimitrios Pagourtzis, a 17-year-old student, opened fire at Santa Fe High School with a shotgun and .38 revolver owned by his father; Pagourtzis killed 10 and injured at least 13 others before surrendering to authorities after a standoff and additional gunfire inside the school. (Pagourtzis reportedly had intended to commit suicide.) Investigators also found undetonated explosive devices in the vicinity. (FURTHER DETAILS PENDING.)

Travis Reinking, 29, opened fire around 3:30 a.m. in the parking lot of a Waffle House in Antioch, and continued shooting as he entered the restaurant. As he attempted to reload his AR-15, a bystander heroically wrestled the rifle away from Reinking, who then fled; he was captured by authorities the following day. Reinking had a history of erratic behavior and run-ins with law enforcement in his home state of Illinois, including claims that he was being stalked and harassed by pop star Taylor Swift. In July 2017, he was arrested at the White House after breaching security in an effort to speak with President Trump, reportedly claiming his right to do so as “a sovereign citizen.”
mental_health_details: Reinking had a history of erratic behavior and run-ins with law enforcement in his home state of Illinois, including claims that he was being stalked and harassed by pop star Taylor Swift. In July 2017, he was arrested at the White House after breaching security in an effort to speak with President Trump, reportedly claiming his right to do so as “a sovereign citizen.”

case: Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School shooting
summary: Nikolas J. Cruz, 19, heavily armed with an AR-15, tactical gear, and “countless magazines” of ammo, according to the Broward County Sheriff, attacked the high school as classes were ending for the day, killing at least 17 people and injuring many others. He was apprehended by authorities shortly after fleeing the campus.
mental_health_details: Cruz had a long history of behavioral problems and had spent time in mental health clinics.

summary: Timothy O'Brien Smith, 28, wearing body armor and well-stocked with ammo, opened fire at a carwash early in the morning in this rural community, killing four people. A fifth victim, though not shot, suffered minor injuries. One of the deceased victims, 25-year-old Chelsie Cline, had been romantically involved with Smith and had broken off the relationship recently, according to her sister. Smith shot himself in the head and died later that night at the hospital.

Kevin Janson Neal, 44, went on an approximately 45-minute shooting spree in the rural community of Rancho Tehama Reserve in Northern California, including shooting up an elementary school, before being killed by law enforcement officers. Neal had also killed his wife at home.

Devin Patrick Kelley, a 26-year-old ex-US Air Force airman, opened fire at the First Baptist Church in Sutherland Springs during Sunday morning services, killing at least 26 people and wounding and injuring 20 others. He left the church and fled in his vehicle after engaging in a gunfight with a local citizen; he soon crashed his vehicle and died from a self-inflicted gunshot wound.
mental_health_details: Kelley had a history of domestic violence, including a court martial and conviction stemming from assaulting his wife and child; he also had a history of cruelty to animals and of stalking and harassing ex-girlfriends, including an underage girl. He reportedly briefly escaped from a mental health facility in 2012.
weapons_obtained_legally: Kelley passed federal criminal background checks; the US Air Force failed to provide information on his criminal history to the FBI
where_obtained: Purchased in April 2016 from an Academy Sports & Outdoors store in San Antonio
weapon_details: Ruger AR-556; Kelley also possessed semiautomatic handguns

summary: Radee Labeeb Prince, 37, fatally shot three people and wounded two others around 9am at Advance Granite Solutions, a home remodeling business where he worked near Baltimore. Hours later he shot and wounded a sixth person at a car dealership in Wilmington, Delaware. He was apprehended that evening following a manhunt by authorities.

Stephen Craig Paddock, 64, fired a barrage of rapid gunfire—using semiautomatic rifles modified with "bump stocks"—at thousands of concertgoers on the Las Vegas Strip late on a Sunday night; Paddock had positioned himself in a corner suite on the 32nd floor of the Mandalay Bay Resort and Casino, where he took aim from windows he'd smashed open. Police responding to the attack found Paddock inside the hotel suite, deceased from a self-inflicted gunshot.
mental_health_details: Perpetrator's history unclear. In 1969 Paddock's father was classified by the FBI as a dangerous psychopath with suicidal tendencies; psychopathy can be heritable (see Mother Jones sourcing).
weapon_type: 23 firearms, mostly rifles; including scopes, and two modified for "fully automatic" firing; two were mounted on tripods
weapon_details: AR-15-style and AK-47-style rifles and "a large cache of ammunition"; four Daniel Defense DDM4 rifles, three FN-15s and other rifles made by Sig Sauer.

700"

summary: Jimmy Lam, 38, fatally shot three coworkers and wounded two others inside a UPS facility in San Francisco. Lam killed himself as law enforcement officers responded to the scene.
mental_health_details: Lam had a history of domestic, work conflict
where_obtained: Unclear; the firearm was stolen in Utah. A second handgun Lam had (also stolen) was unused in the attack.
weapon_details: MAC-10-style “assault pistol”; 30-round magazine. An additional box of ammunition.

summary: John Robert Neumann, Jr., 45, a former employee of manufacturer Fiamma Inc. fatally shot five workers at the company, and then killed himself on the scene. He'd been fired from the company in April. The attack took place a week before the one-year anniversary of the Orlando nightclub massacre.

Esteban Santiago, 26, flew from Alaska to Fort Lauderdale, where he opened fire in the baggage claim area of the airport, killing five and wounding six before police aprehended him. (Numerous other people were reportedly injured while fleeing during the panic.)
mental_health_details: Among other signs, Santiago had gone to a FBI office in Anchorage and complained that his mind was being controlled by the CIA.

summary: Arcan Cetin, 20, killed a teen girl and three women in the cosmetics section of a Macy’s department store at the Cascade Mall. A man was critically wounded in the shooting and taken to Harborview Medical Center in Seattle, where he died. Cetin was apprehended by police a few hours after the shooting while driving a car near his residence.
mental_health_details: According to the Cetin's stepfather he had "mental health issues"; court records showed that he suffered from anxiety and depression.

summary: Gavin Long, 29, a former Marine who served in Iraq, killed three police offers responding to a 911 call, and wounded three others. He was killed in a shoot-out with other officers responding to the scene. Prior to the attack, Long posted prolifically on social media, where he expressed admiration for the cop killer in Dallas 10 days prior.
weapon_type: Two semiautomatic rifles; one semiautomatic handgun
weapon_details: IWI Tavor SAR 5.56 caliber rifle, Springfield XD 9, 9mm

summary: Micah Xavier Johnson, a 25-year-old Army veteran, targeted police at a peaceful Black Lives Matter protest, killing five officers and injuring nine others as well as two civilians. After a prolonged standoff in a downtown building, law enforcement killed Johnson using a robot-delivered bomb.
weapon_details: Izhmash-Saiga 5.45mm (AK-style) semiautomatic rifle with large capacity magazines; Glock 9mm handgun, .25-caliber semiautomatic handgun

summary: Omar Mateen, 29, attacked the Pulse nighclub in Orlando in the early morning hours of June 12. He was killed by law enforcement who raided the club after a prolonged standoff.
where_obtained: Shooting center in Port St. Lucie, Florida
weapon_details: Sig Sauer MCX rifle, Glock 17 9mm; high-capacity magazines (30 rounds)

summary: Cedric L. Ford, who worked as a painter at a manufacturing company, shot victims from his car and at his workplace before being killed by police at the scene. Shortly before the rampage he had been served with a restraining order.
weapon_details: Zastava Serbia AK-47-style rifle, Glock Model 22 .40-caliber handgun; high-capacity magazines (30 rounds)

summary: Jason B. Dalton, a driver for Uber, apparently selected his victims randomly as he went on a rampage over several hours in three different locations, including five people he shot in the parking lot of a Cracker Barrel restaurant. He was "arrested without incident" at a downtown Kalamazoo bar about six hours after the rampage began.

Syed Rizwan Farook left a Christmas party held at Inland Regional Center, later returning with Tashfeen Malik and the two opened fire, killing 14 and wounding 21, ten critically. The two were later killed by police as they fled in an SUV.
where_obtained: The suspects purchased their handguns in the United States; the assault rifles were purchased by a third party.
weapon_type: Two assault rifles and two semi-automatic pistols were used in the attack. Police found a remote controlled explosive device at the scene of the crime. At the home were 12 pipe bombs, 2,500 rounds for the AR-15 variants, 2,000 rounds for the pistols, and several hundred for a .22 calibre rifle. In the suspects' car were an additional 1,400 rounds for the rifles and 200 for the handguns.
weapon_details: Two semiautomatic AR-15-style rifles—one a DPMS A-15, the other a Smith & Wesson M&P15, both with .223 calibre ammunition. Two 9mm semiautomatic handguns. High capacity magazines.

summary: Robert Lewis Dear, 57, shot and killed a police officer and two citizens when he opened fire at a Planned Parenthood health clinic in Colorado Springs, Colorado. Nine others were wounded. Dear was arrested after an hours-long standoff with police.
mental_health_details: The judge in the case has not publicly released Dear's medical and mental health records. As of April 5, 2016, Dear was undergoing a competency evaluation. Dear had a history of disputes with his relatives and neighbors. At a hearing in December 2015, he said, "I am a warrior for the babies."
weapon_details: Reportedly an AK-47 style semiautomatic rifle and others. Authorities had not released details on Dear's weapons as of April 2016.

summary: 26-year-old Chris Harper Mercer opened fire at Umpqua Community College in southwest Oregon. The gunman shot himself to death after being wounded in a shootout with police.
mental_health_details: Harper-Mercer's mother said in multiple online postings that he had Asperger's syndrome. Harper-Mercer graduated from the Switzer Learning Center, a school for students with special needs, emotional difficulties, autism and Asperger's syndrome.
where_obtained: From the home he shared with his mother. All were legally obtained by either Harper/Mercer or family members.
weapon_type: Five pistols, one rifle, five magazines of ammunition
weapon_details: 9 mm Glock pistol, .40 caliber Smith & Wesson, .40 caliber Taurus pistol, .556 caliber Del-Ton; (ammo details unclear)

summary: Kuwaiti-born Mohammod Youssuf Abdulazeez, 24, a naturalized US citizen, opened fire at a Naval reserve center, and then drove to a military recruitment office where he shot and killed four Marines and a Navy service member, and wounded a police officer and another military service member. He was then fatally shot in an exchange of gunfire with law enforcement officers responding to the attack.
mental_health_details: Abdulazeez "had suffered for years from depression and possibly from bipolar disorder," according to a representative of the family. (NYT, July 20 2015)
weapons_obtained_legally: Yes ("some of the weapons were purchased legally and some of them may not have been")

summary: Dylann Storm Roof, 21, shot and killed 9 people after opening fire at the Emanuel AME Church in Charleston, South Carolina. According to a roommate, he had allegedly been “planning something like that for six months."
where_obtained: Shooter's Choice gun store in West Columbia, South Carolina

summary: Sergio Valencia del Toro, 27, in what officials say was a random act, shot and killed three people including an 11-year-old girl before turning the gun on himself.
mental_health_details: While serving in the Air Force, he went to an emergency walk-in clinic because of concerns over his mood swings, and had either sought or been ordered to behavioral health interventions, according to Fox 6 Now. In a 2014 risk assessment with a psychologist at an outpatient clinic in Appleton, Valencia del Toro recalled thinking previously: "If I'm gonna take myself out, I might as well take other people with me." The police report obtained by Fox 6 says that Valencia del Toro had a history of depression, suicidal and occassionally homicidal thoughts, and alcoholism. He was intoxicated on the day of the shooting.
weapon_details: Details unclear, but after the shooting, police found eight guns in total in Valencia del Toro's home, including handguns, shotguns, and rifles, plus and more than 1,000 rounds of ammunition. He took two weapons and ammunition to the bridge.

summary:
Jaylen Fryberg, 15, using a .40-caliber Berretta, shot five 
students at Marysville High School, including two of his cousins and three friends, killing all but one. Fryberg arranged to meet them for lunch in the school cafeteria by text. Fryberg was reportedly well-liked at the school and there was not believed to be any ill-will between him and his victims. He committed suicide at the scene.
mental_health_details: Fryberg was well-liked and allegedly happy, but was also upset about a girl and had posted emotional social media messages. No definitive signs of mental health problems.

summary: Elliot Rodger, 22, shot three people to death in the college town of Isla Vista near the University of California, Santa Barbara. He also shot others as he drove around town, and injured others by striking them with is vehicle. He committed suicide by shooting himself in his car as police closed in. Prior to the rampage, Rodger stabbed three people to death at his apartment.
mental_health_details: Rodger was never hospitalized due to mental illness, but had a long history of mental health issues dating back to his childhood, and received treatment from multiple counselors leading up to his rampage. According to The Independent, Rodger had considered suicide but had no history of violence. Just before his rampage, he sent a 137-page manifesto to multiple people.
weapon_type: Three semi-automatic handguns and two hunting knives
weapon_details: Two Sig Sauer P226 semiautomatic pistols and Glock 34 pistol, and hundreds of rounds of ammo. A 6- inchand 8-inch “SRK” and “Boar Hunter” hunting knives.

summary: Army Specialist Ivan Lopez, 34, opened fire at the Fort Hood Army Post in Texas, killing three and wounding at least 12 others before shooting himself in the head after engaging with military police. Lt. Gen. Mark A. Milley told reporters that Lopez "had behavioral health and mental health" issues.
mental_health_details: Lopez "had a long history of troubling behavior," according to the Washington Post, including a history of decieving others, problems in his personal life, and financial difficulties. However, officials found that Lopez exhibited no signals that he could be violent. In the year leading up to the attack, he sought treatment for medical and behavioral health ailments.
where_obtained: Local gun store in Killeen, Guns Galore

summary: Cherie Lash Rhoades, 44, opened fire at the Cedarville Rancheria Tribal Office and Community Center, killing four and wounding two. After running out of ammunition, Rhoades grabbed a butcher knife and stabbed another person.
weapon_type: Two handguns and a butcher knife

summary: Aaron Alexis, 34, a military veteran and contractor from Texas, opened fire in the Navy installation, killing 12 people and wounding 8 before being shot dead by police.
mental_health_details: Had told Rhode Island police the prior month that he'd "heard voices"; had been undergoing mental health treatment with Veterans Affairs since August 2013.
weapon_type: Sawed-off shotgun, 2 boxes of shells; also a .45-caliber handgun taken from a security guard he shot at the scene.

summary: Pedro Vargas, 42, set fire to his apartment, killed six people in the complex, and held another two hostages at gunpoint before a SWAT team stormed the building and fatally shot him.
mental_health_details: His mother told authorities her son had been acting strangely and needed a psychiatric evaluation.

summary: John Zawahri, 23, armed with a homemade assault rifle and high-capacity magazines, killed his brother and father at home and then headed to Santa Monica College, where he was eventually killed by police.
mental_health_details: He was known as a solitary teen who regularly ditched class and had an interest in assault weapons; he had been admitted to UCLA's psychiatric ward for a brief period.
where_obtained: Assembled a rifle out of component parts.
weapon_type: Assault rifle, high capacity magazines, antique handgun
weapon_details: .223-caliber semi-automatic assault rifle, about 40 high capacity magazines, "black powder" handgun (likely antique)

summary: Dennis Clark III, 27, shot and killed his girlfriend in their shared apartment, and then shot two witnesses in the building's parking lot and a third victim in another apartment, before being killed by police.
weapon_details: .40 caliber semi-automatic handgun, pistol grip shotgun

summary: Kurt Myers, 64, shot six people in neighboring towns, killing two in a barbershop and two at a car care business, before being killed by officers in a shootout after a nearly 19-hour standoff.
Adam Lanza, 20, shot his mother dead at their home then drove to Sandy Hook Elementary school. He forced his way inside and opened fire, killing 20 children and six adults before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: Lanza had a history of serious mental health problems that were known to his family and others, as detailed in a post-massacre investigation by Connecticut authorities.
weapon_type: Two semiautomatic handguns, one rifle (assault), one shotgun (assault)
weapon_details: 10mm Glock, 9mm SIG Sauer P226 semiautomatic handguns; .223 Bushmaster XM15-E2S semiautomatic rifle; Izhmash Saiga-12 12-gauge semiautomatic shotgun

summary: Andrew Engeldinger, 36, upon learning he was being fired, went on a shooting rampage, killing the business owner, three fellow employees, and a UPS driver. He then killed himself.
mental_health_details: His family worried about his "paranoia and delusions" for at least two years prior, and tried to get him to seek treatment.

summary: U.S. Army veteran Wade Michael Page, 40, opened fire in a Sikh gurdwara before he died from a self-inflicted gunshot would during a shootout with police.
mental_health_details: His Army friends once broke into his apartment, fearing he'd commit suicide in the '90s. A psychiatric nurse who lived downstairs from Page said it was "obvious" he had a mental illness.

summary: James Holmes, 24, opened fire in a movie theater during the opening night of "The Dark Night Rises" and was later arrested outside.
mental_health_details: He saw at least three mental health professionals before dropping out of his university.
where_obtained: Gander Mountain stores in Thornton and Aurora, Colo.; Bass Pro Shop in Denver, Colo.; BulkAmmo.com
weapon_type: Two semiautomatic handguns, one rifle (assault), one shotgun
weapon_details: Two .40-caliber Glock semiautomatic handguns; .223-caliber Smith & Wesson M&P15 semiautomatic rifle; 12-gauge Remington 870 pump-action shotgun

summary: Ian Stawicki, 40, gunned down four patrons at a cafe, and another person during a carjacking nearby, then shot himself as police closed in. (He died later that day in a Seattle hospital.)
mental_health_details: His family said he was mentally ill
where_obtained: Bull's Eye Shooter Supply in Tacoma, Wash.

summary: One L. Goh, 43, a former student, opened fire in a nursing classroom. He fled the scene by car and was arrested nearby a few hours later.
mental_health_details: A former instructor at Oikos described him as "mentally unstable" and "paranoid."

summary: Jeong Soo Paek, 59, returned to a Korean spa from which he'd been kicked out after an altercation. He gunned down two of his sisters and their husbands before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: His sister worried about his homicidal tendencies; she said his mental health had been deteriorating and that he had threatened to commit suicide with his gun.

summary: Scott Evans Dekraai, 42, opened fire inside a hair salon and was later arrested. Victims killed in the attack included his ex-wife, who Dekraai had a history of violently abusing, according to court records. The two had also been involved in a bitter custody battle.
mental_health_details: He suffered from bipolar disorder, mood swings, and PTSD. After an assault on his elderly stepfather, he was sentenced in 2008 to a year of anger management therapy.
weapon_details: .45-caliber Heckler & Koch, 9mm Springfield semiautomatic handguns; .44 Magnum Smith & Wesson revolver

summary: Eduardo Sencion, 32, opened fire at an International House of Pancakes restaurant and later died from a self-inflicted gunshot wound.
mental_health_details: He was diagnosed with paranoid schizophrenia as a teenager and feared demons were out to get him.
weapon_details: AK-47 Norinco Arms variant, AK-47 Romarm Cugir variant rifles; .38-caliber Colt revolver

summary: Jared Loughner, 22, opened fire outside a Safeway during a constituent meeting with Congresswoman Gabrielle Giffords (D-Ariz.) before he was subdued by bystanders and arrested.
mental_health_details: His symptoms pointed to various possible mental illness diagnoses, such as schizophrenia and delusional disorder. He also experimented with pot and hallucinogens.

summary: Omar S. Thornton, 34, shot up his Hartford Beer Distributor workplace after facing disciplinary issues, then committed suicide.
mental_health_details: He apparently was driven over the edge by unaddressed, ongoing racism against him at work
where_obtained: Gun dealer in East Windsor, Conn.

summary: Maurice Clemmons, 37, a felon who was out on bail for child-rape charges, entered a coffee shop on a Sunday morning and shot four police officers who had gone there to use their laptops before their shifts. Clemmons, who was wounded fleeing the scene, was later shot dead by a police officer in Seattle after a two-day manhunt.
mental_health_details: He had a history of erratic, bizarre behavior. He once asked his family to get naked for 5 minutes on Sunday; he said he thought the world would end and that he was Jesus.
where_obtained: Stolen from an individual in Seattle.
weapon_details: 9mm Glock 17 semiautomatic handgun; .38-caliber Smith & Wesson revolver

summary: Army psychiatrist Nidal Malik Hasan, 39, opened fire on an Army base in an attack linked to Islamist extremism. Hasan was injured during the attack and later arrested.
mental_health_details: Medical officials at Walter Reed Army Medical Center and the Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences raised concerns prior to the shooting regarding Hasan's aloof and erratic behavior and extremist Islamic views.

summary: Jiverly Wong, 41, opened fire at an American Civic Association center for immigrants before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: He apparently harbored growing paranoia toward cops. He also sent a delusional letter to a local TV station right before the shooting.
where_obtained: Gander Mountain in Johnson City, N.Y.

summary: Robert Stewart, 45, opened fire at a nursing home where his estranged wife worked before he was shot and arrested by a police officer.
mental_health_details: His estranged wife told her workplace that her husband had an "unstable mental state or (was) mentally ill."
where_obtained: Local sporting goods stores and individuals

summary: Disgruntled employee Wesley Neal Higdon, 25, shot up an Atlantis Plastics factory after he was escorted out of his workplace for an argument with a supervisor. Higdon shot the supervisor outside the factory before opening fire on coworkers inside. He then committed suicide.
mental_health_details: He called his girlfriend two hours before the shooting to say he was going to kill his boss.

summary: Steven Kazmierczak, 27, opened fire in a lecture hall, then shot and killed himself before police arrived.
mental_health_details: He had a long history of mental health struggles; after high school, his parents placed him at a psychiatric treatment center. He told friends he left the Army after six months due to a psychological discharge.
where_obtained: Online and gun retailers in Champaign, Ill.
weapon_details: 9mm Glock 19, Hi-Point CF380, 9mm Kurz SIG Sauer P232 semiautomatic handguns; 12-gauge Remington Sportsman 48 sawed-off shotgun

summary: Charles "Cookie" Lee Thornton, 52, went on a rampage at the city hall before being shot and killed by police.
mental_health_details: He was known for histrionics and disruptions at city council meetings. His mounting debt was a stressor.
where_obtained: Taken in burglary and from fallen police officer
weapon_details: .40-caliber Smith & Wesson semiautomatic handgun; .44 Magnum Smith & Wesson Model 29 revolver

summary: Robert A. Hawkins, 19, opened fire inside Westroads Mall before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: He had been treated in the past for depression and ADHD.

summary: Off-duty sheriff's deputy Tyler Peterson, 20, opened fire inside an apartment after an argument at a homecoming party. He fled the scene and later committed suicide.
mental_health_details: The families of victims filed a wrongful death lawsuit against the county arguing that the police department should have evaluated the gunman's mental health before hiring him.
where_obtained: Issued by Forest County Sheriff's Department

summary: Virginia Tech student Seung-Hui Cho, 23, opened fire on his school's campus before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: A district court ruled Cho was "an imminent danger" to himself and others as a result of mental illness two years earlier, and directed Cho to seek treatment.
where_obtained: Purchased variously online and from Roanoke Firearms in Roanoke, Va.

summary: Sulejman Talović, 18, rampaged through the shopping center until he was shot dead by police.
mental_health_details: According to one relative, he was violent and had the mental capacity of a child. (But accounts from others did not indicate this about the shooter.)
where_obtained: Purchased variously from Sportsman's Fast Cash in West Valley City, Utah and individuals
weapon_details: Mossberg Maverick 88 Field shotgun; .38-caliber Smith & Wesson M36 revolver

summary: Charles Carl Roberts, 32, shot 10 young girls in a one-room schoolhouse in Bart Township, killing 5, before taking his own life.
mental_health_details: He told his wife that he'd molested two young relatives 20 years ago.
where_obtained: Local stores in Nickel Mines, Penn.
weapon_type: One semiautomatic handgun, one rifle, one shotgun
weapon_details: Springfield semiautomatic handgun; .30-06 Ruger bolt-action rifle; 12-gauge Browning pump-action shotgun

summary: Kyle Aaron Huff, 28, opened fire at a rave afterparty in the Capitol Hill neighborhood of Seattle before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: Police were unable to find any record that he had been treated for mental illness or was on psychiatric medication.
where_obtained: Various sporting goods stores in Kalispell, Mont.
weapon_type: Two semiautomatic handguns, one rifle (assault), one shotgun
weapon_details: .40-caliber Ruger, one other semiautomatic handgun; Bushmaster XM15 E2S semiautomatic rifle; 12-gauge Winchester Defender pump-action shotgun with extended tube and pistol grip

summary: Former postal worker Jennifer Sanmarco, 44, shot dead a former neighbor then drove to the mail processing plant where she used to work. Inside, she opened fire, killing six employees before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: She was placed on retirement disability for psychological reasons. Fellow employees described her behavior as increasingly bizarre. She believed the Postal Service employees were conspiring against her.
where_obtained: Pawn shops in Grants and Gallup, N.M.

summary: Jeffrey Weise, 16, murdered his grandfather, who was a police officer, and grandfather's girlfriend. Weise then drove his grandfather's squad car to Red Lake Senior High School and opened fire on the reservation campus, killing another seven people before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: He voluntarily visited a a psychiatric ward. He was hospitalized at least once for suicidal tendencies and was taking Prozac.
where_obtained: Glock and Remington stolen from grandfather
weapon_details: .40-caliber Glock 23, .22-caliber Ruger semiautomatic handguns; 12-gauge Remington 870 shotgun

summary: Living Church of God member Terry Michael Ratzmann, 44, opened fire at a church meeting at a Sheraton hotel before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: Neighbors said he suffered from depression and had a drinking problem.

summary: Nathan Gale, 25, possibly upset about the breakup of Pantera, gunned down former Pantera guitarist Dimebag Darrell and three others at a Damageplan show before a police officer fatally shot Gale.
mental_health_details: He was discharged from the military because he was a paranoid schizophrenic.
where_obtained: Received as a gift from mother

summary: Assembly line worker Douglas Williams, 48, opened fire at his Lockheed Martin workplace in a racially motivated attack before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: His cousin said he was depressed and "going through a lot of things."
weapon_type: One semiautomatic handgun, two rifles, one derringer, one shotgun
weapon_details: .45-caliber Ruger P90 semiautomatic handgun; .22-caliber rifle with scope, .223-caliber Ruger Mini-14 rifle; 12-gauge Winchester 1300 shotgun; .22 Magnum derringer

summary: Fired employee William D. Baker, 66, opened fire at his former Navistar workplace before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: He had a criminal past, including a sexual assault conviction.
where_obtained: Some purchased from Pepper Sports in Glen Ellyn, Ill.
weapon_type: Two rifles, one revolver, one shotgun
weapon_details: SKS 1954R, .30-caliber Winchester rifles; 12-gauge Remington pump-action shotgun; .38-caliber revolver

summary: Michael McDermott, 42, opened fire on co-workers at Edgewater Technology and was later arrested.
mental_health_details: Psychiatrist guessed he had schizophrenia, but McDermott had researched how to fake a mental illness on the internet. Defense lawyer described history of suicide attempts and mental illness dating back to teen years. Jury rejected his insanity defense.
weapon_type: One semiautomatic handgun, one rifle (assault), one shotgun
weapon_details: .32-caliber Retolaza semiautomatic handgun; AK-47 variant semiautomatic rifle; 12-gauge Winchester 1300 pump-action shotgun

summary: Hotel employee Silvio Leyva, 36, gunned down four coworkers at the Radisson Bay Harbor Inn before killing a woman outside who refused to give him her car. He was arrested shortly after the shootings.
mental_health_details: His brother called him "unbalanced" and mentally ill.
where_obtained: One purchased from Big E's in Tampa, Fla.
weapon_details: 9mm Lorcin semiautomatic handgun; .38-caliber Charter Arms revolver

summary: Byran Koji Uyesugi, 40, a Xerox service technician, opened fire inside the building with a 9mm Glock. He fled and was later apprehended by police.
mental_health_details: A psychiatrist, testifying for the prosecution,said he suffered from schizophrenia.
where_obtained: Hunting Supplies of Hawaii (The Armory) in Honolulu, Hawaii

summary: Larry Gene Ashbrook, 47, opened fire inside the Wedgwood Baptist Church during a prayer rally before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: His siblings decribed him as a paranoid schizophrenic.
where_obtained: Trader's Village flea market in Grand Prairie, Texas

summary: Day trader Mark O. Barton, 44, who had recently lost a substantial sum of money, went on a shooting spree through two day-trading firms. He started at the All-Tech Investment Group, where he worked, then went on to Momentum Securities. He fled and hours later, after being cornered by police outside a gas station, committed suicide. (Two days before the spree, he killed his wife and two children with a hammer.)
mental_health_details: In letters, he details his deep depression and downward spiral.
where_obtained: Glock purchased from gun store in Warner Robins, Ga.
weapon_details: .45-caliber Colt 1911-A1, 9mm Glock 17, .25-caliber Raven Arms MP-25 semiautomatic handguns; .22-caliber Harrington & Richardson revolver

summary: Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, opened fire throughout Columbine High School before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: Harris was an alleged psychopath; Klebold was depressed and suicidal.
where_obtained: Purchased variously at Tanner Gun Show in Denver, Colo. and from an individual
weapon_type: One semiautomatic handgun (assault), one rifle (assault), two shotguns
weapon_details: 9mm Intratec DC-9 semiautomatic handgun; 9mm Hi-Point 995 carbine rifle; 12-gauge sawed-off Savage Stevens 311D, 12-gauge sawed-off Savage Springfield 67H pump-action shotguns

summary: After he was expelled for having a gun in his locker, Kipland P. Kinkel, 15, a freshman at Thurston High, went on a shooting spree, killing his parents at home and two students at school. Five classmates wrestled Kipland to the ground before he was arrested.
mental_health_details: Doctors testified that he was a paranoid schizophrenic who suffered from hallucinations
where_obtained: Purchased variously from friend and father, and stolen from father
weapon_details: 9mm Glock, .22-caliber Ruger semiautomatic handguns, .22-caliber Ruger rifle

summary: Mitchell Scott Johnson, 13, and Andrew Douglas Golden, 11, two juveniles, ambushed students and teachers as they left the school; they were apprehended by police at the scene.
mental_health_details: Boys displayed unruly and aggressive behavior. They picked on kids and made threats about killing people.
weapon_type: Two semiautomatic handguns, two rifles, three revolvers, two derringers
weapon_details: FIE 380, .380-caliber Star semiautomatic handguns; .44 Magnum Ruger, .30-06 Remington 742, .30-caliber Universal M-1 carbine replica rifles; .38-caliber Charter Arms, .357-caliber Ruger Security Six, .38-caliber Smith & Wesson revolvers; .22-caliber Double Deuce Buddie two-shot, .38-caliber Davis Industries two-shot derringers

summary: Lottery worker Matthew Beck, 35, gunned down four bosses over a salary dispute before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: He had been hospitalized for psychiatric reasons and had a history of depression

summary: Former Caltrans employee Arturo Reyes Torres, 41, opened fire at a maintenance yard after he was fired for allegedly selling government materials he'd stolen from work. He was shot dead by police.
mental_health_details: He was disgruntled after being fired.
where_obtained: B&B Gun Sales in Orange County, Calif.

summary: Ex-con Hastings Arthur Wise, 43, opened fire at the R.E. Phelon Company in retaliation for being fired after an argument with a supervisor. He attempted suicide by ingesting insecticide, failed, and was executed by the state of South Carolina eight years later.
mental_health_details: An ex-con, he had been freed from prison, although he displayed violent tendencies.

summary: Fired city park employee Clifton McCree, 41, opened fire on former coworkers he called "racist devils" inside their municipal trailer in an act of revenge after failing a drug test. He then committed suicide.
mental_health_details: Co-workers complained about his threats and verbal abuse. His supervisors asked him to get a psychiatric evaluation. He lost his job, which relatives said drove his depression.

summary: Disgruntled former metallurgist James Daniel Simpson, 28, opened fire throughout the Walter Rossler Company where he had worked before exiting the building and committing suicide.
mental_health_details: He was likely angry because he was given an assignment at work he didn't like. But acquaintances didn't know why he'd come back and kill.

summary: Former airman Dean Allen Mellberg, 20, opened fire inside a hospital at the Fairchild Air Force Base before he was shot dead by a military police officer outside.
mental_health_details: He was repeatedly diagnosed with emotional problems during his two years of service.

summary: Nathan Dunlap, 19, a recently fired Chuck E. Cheese's employee, went on a rampage through his former workplace and was arrested the following day. He now awaits execution on death row.
mental_health_details: While he was in prison awaiting trial, he started acting bizarre by stripping naked and playing with his feces, apparently to avoid the death penalty. A state doctor testified that Dunlap was was faking his mental illness.

summary: Colin Ferguson, 35, opened fire on an eastbound Long Island Rail Road train as it approached a Garden City station. He was later arrested.
mental_health_details: Psychiatrists and others said he suffered from racial paranoia and was obsessed with nonexistent conspiracies. His landlord said he had "delusions of grandeur."
where_obtained: Turner's Outdoorsman in Signal Hill, Calif.

summary: Army Sgt. Kenneth Junior French, 22, opened fire inside Luigi's Italian restaurant while ranting about gays in the military before he was shot and arrested by police.
mental_health_details: He had an abusive father, who committed suicide.

summary: Failed businessman Gian Luigi Ferri, 55, opened fire throughout an office building before he committed suicide inside as police pursued him.
mental_health_details: He was down on his luck because of failed business decisions. One acquaintance said, "He was the least likely guy you can imagine doing something like that."  His ex-wife said he "hated violence."
where_obtained: Super Pawn and Pacific Tactical Weapons, both in Las Vegas, Nev.
weapon_details: Two Intratec DC-9, .45-caliber Colt semiautomatic handguns

summary: John T. Miller, 50, killed four child-support workers in a county office building before turning the gun on himself.  Miller was upset about a court order garnishing his paycheck to cover overdue child-support payments.
mental_health_details: The day before the shooting, he told child-support collection office workers that he was considering suicide. He had been convicted of felonious assault for pointing a revolver at police officers responding to a domestic violence report at this girlfriend's apartment.

summary: Former Lindhurst High School student Eric Houston, 20, angry about various personal failings, killed three students and a teacher at the school before surrendering to police after an eight-hour standoff. He was later sentenced to death.
mental_health_details: He suffered violent physical abuse as a child. He claimed a teacher had sexually abused him, but the truth of that allegation was contested.

summary: Laid-off postal worker Thomas McIlvane, 31, opened fire at his former workplace before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: Police revoked his CCW permit after determining he was mentally unstable.

summary: Former graduate student Gang Lu, 28, went on a rampage on campus and then committed suicide at the scene.
mental_health_details: He was described as darkly disturbed and isolated.
where_obtained: Fin & Feather in Iowa City, Iowa

summary: George Hennard, 35, drove his pickup truck into a Luby's cafeteria and opened fire before committing suicide.
mental_health_details: Acquaintances described him as troubled, unstable, combative, and misogynistic. He made convenience store employees "nervous."
where_obtained: Mike's Gun Shop in Henderson, Nev.

summary: Officers were called to 537 Willow Park Road just after 8:00 a.m. on July 29, 2020 for a welfare check. When they arrived, they found five people dead inside the house. All five sustained what appeared to be gunshot wounds.  In what appeared to be a murder-suicide, 44-year-old John Nelson fatally shot his wife and three children before turning the gun on himself. It is believed that the deaths occurred on July 28.
Seven people were shot, four of them fatally, in a hail of gunfire in Paterson, NJ after 11 pm in what has been called a gang-related incident. The case is unsolved.

Policed responded to a 911 call in Lafayette, WI, finding two dead (including the suspected assailant Ritchie German, Jr.) and two others injured. The police subsequently went to the home of the suspected assailant, finding three dead victims (the suspected assailant’s mother, brother, and nephew).

According to the police, Gerry Dean Zaragoza, 26, went on a shooting rampage in the San Fernando Valley killing four (including his father and brother) and injuring two others (including his mother). The other two slain victims were a mother of four with whom Zaragoza had been obsessed for some time and a man who was shot on a bus. The shooting spree started in Canoga Park, then to North Hollywood, Sherman Oaks, and Van Nuys where Zaragoza was arrested and is awaiting trial.

On July 8, 2019, Armond Johnson allegedly shot and killed his former girlfriend inside her residence before setting the house on fire (killing their 6-year-old son and her 2-year-old daughter) and then fleeing the scene. According to the police, Johnson returned to the crime scene early the following morning and shot and killed a neighbor in a vacant field adjacent to his residence. Johnson was charged and is awaiting trial.
Five victims were shot to death in police say was in connection with drug activity. Anthony Watkins and Terrance Wesley were both arrested and are awaiting trial in connection to the shootings.
Four related men were shot and killed inside an injured victim's home. The police believe the incident was related to drugs, as drugs and weapons were found in the home. The case remains unsolved.

Chad Isaak, a veteran and chiropractor, went to the company that managed his mobile home park and shot and stabbed four employees there. It remains unclear if he had any relationship with the victims or what the precise motive was. Isaak was convicted and sentenced to life in prison.

Richard Emery had been dating his girlfriend for approximately a year and a half. Her husband had passed away after a six-year battle with cancer about six months prior to the beginning of their relationship. He had moved into their home, and no one reported any signs of domestic violence, conflict, or mental illness. He shot and killed his girlfriend, her two children, and her mother before fleeing in a vehicle. When stopped by police, he shot at the officers and ran off on foot, attempting to carjack a woman. When her car wouldn't start, he stabbed her (nonfatally) and was eventually caught the next morning in a convenience store bathroom, suffering from two bullet wounds. Emery has been charged and is awaiting trial.

Paul Caneiro killed his brother and his family, presumably for a financial motive. The two brothers had established businesses together, but his brother was much more successful than Paul (bigger share of businesses, more money, bigger house, etc.) Several years prior to the incident, Paul was in a car accident that required multiple surgeries and caused immense emotional and physical pain (he was awarded a $120,000 settlement for his medical expenses). The once booming business that the brothers shared had fallen on tough times, and Paul’s brother had recently found out that Paul had stolen $75,000 from the business. the brother indicated that he wanted to sever his business relationship with Paul, and had sent his resume to other companies, especially looking for a job in California. Paul shot and killed his brother and his sister-in-law before stabbing their two children. He then lit their house on fire and drove home, lighting his own home on fire to make it look like a vendetta against the extended family. Caneiro has been charged and is awaiting trial.

A man was recently estranged from his wife and had lost his local job, working instead out of state. Their oldest son had Williams syndrome. He killed his wife and three young children before committing suicide.

Dwight Jones reportedly had a history of mental illness and domestic violence. He had used abusive language towards his son, and then beat up his wife. After his arrest for domestic violence, he was court-ordered to undergo a mental health evaluation and was involuntarily committed to a behavioral health facility. After nine years, he posted a YouTube video detailing his beliefs that there was a conspiracy between his ex-wife, psychiatrist, the law firm, and the local government to keep his son away from him. According to the authorities, Jones then killed his psychiatrist, two paralegals who worked for his wife's law firm, a man who was renting the office of his son's therapist, and two friends. Jones took his own life.

Ja'Vonne DuPree was friends with the victims and was staying at their house at the time of the murders. He shot the four victims, ransacked the house, and stole their car. Dupree was convicted and given a life sentence.

Karon McVay came to his girlfriend's cousin's house and shot/stabbed four to death, leaving the three-year-old daughter of his girlfriend's cousin alive. He later returned to the scene when police arrived and pretended to be a normal concerned citizen. He had a history of arson and possibly domestic violence, and served time in prison. Charges against McVay are pending.
According to the police, Keith Kroeker shot his wife and three young children before setting their house and barn ablaze and killing himself.

Returning after having bought marijuana, Lionel Parks and an accomplice, both armed, ordered everyone in the home to take off their clothes and hand over cellphones, money and jewelry, prosecutors said.  They then discovered a woman in a back bedroom with a cellphone and reportedly became "agitated." The two "started executing the victims by shooting them in the head as they were lying on the ground," according to a court document detailing the charges. Four victims died at the scene. There were two survivors of the shooting. One escaped by playing dead and was able to later identify Parks. The other remained on life support, unable to respond to touch or sound, until she died more than 10 months later. Parks was arrested for murder, and charges against him are pending trial.

After serving time for killing his pregnant wife in 1991, Gregory Green married the daughter of the pastor that had helped secure his release. He later tortured and tied her up, making her watch as he killed their children. Green pleaded guilty and was sentenced to prison.

A drunken James Steven Jennex sent a text message to a friend apologizing in advance for his actions and then fired a bullet into the heads of each of three developmentally disabled men in his care before setting his Temecula-area home ablaze and killing himself with a .357 revolver blast to the head.  The fire at the Renee Jennex Small Family Home killed a fourth developmentally disabled man and burned all five people beyond recognition. Investigators pulled a gas can from the rubble.
Mark Short killed his wife, three children, and the family dog before committing suicide.

A man was lured to the Likquid Lounge because he owed money from a drug deal. Nicholas Tartaglione allegedly strangled him. According to the authorities, the victim’s three companions were then taken elsewhere by Tartaglione and his accomplices and were fatally shot, their bodies discovered eight months later. Tartaglione was charged and is awaiting trial.

In retaliation for the murder of a friend, two gunmen opened fire at a backyard party, killing five and wounding three. Police have determined the suspect with a handgun shot in a manner that forced party-goers towards a gap in a fence where a suspect with an AK-47 rifle waited. The charges against one of the suspects were dropped while the other was acquitted.

A 26-year-old shot and killed his mother, father, and two younger sisters in their family home before being killed by police. The suspect also set the house on fire, impeding police efforts to rescue any potential survivors.

After a welfare check, police found the bodies of six family members inside their home. Five of the victims, including children ages 10 and 13, died from sharp or blunt force injuries, while the final victim was shot to death. The motive was robbery, and the murders were designed as a cover-up. Diego Uribe Cruz and Jafeth Ramos both pleaded guilty to the murders.

Firefighters responding to a house fire in Rochester, N.Y. discovered four victims and quickly determined the house was a crime scene. No further details are available. police are investigating it as a homicide.

State police found two adults and two children; the adults were shot while the children died of smoke inhalation from the fire, apparently set to cover up evidence of the murders. The assailant was convicted and given a life sentence.

Six people were killed while camping on one of the victim's newly purchased land. Four men and a 6-year-old boy were shot after getting help pulling their vehicle out of mud, and a woman was beaten to death. William Hudson was convicted and sentenced to death.
A married couple and their elderly mothers  were shot to death by an unknown assailant inside their mobile home. The case remains unsolved.

A fire destroyed a rural home, revealing the bodies of a family of six inside. Autopsies led authorities to conclude that Scott Westerhuis had shot and killed his wife and four school-age children and then set fire to their home before killing himself.

Five family members were found dead in their home. Authorities said Brian S. Short, 45, killed his wife and teenagers before killing himself. Acquaintances and family members said Short was depressed because his Internet business was struggling.

Jody Herring, 40, was tackled by onlookers after he fatally shot a social worker outside a state office building. She had handled a case involving Herring's daughter. Hours later, three of Herring's relatives were found shot dead in their home. Herring pleaded guilty and was sentenced to life without parole.

Thomas Jesse Lee pleaded guilty but mentally ill to five counts of malice murder in the slayings of his wife, her parents, her daughter and a family friend. Their bodies were found at a home where Lee had been staying. Lee is sentenced to life in prison.

Six people were killed at three locations in suburban Philadelphia. After a daylong manhunt, police found the body of suspect Bradley William Stone, a former Marine, in the woods near his home. Stone's ex-wife and five of her family members died.

Police said Jody Hunt, 39, drove to three locations around Morgantown and shot an ex-girlfriend, a cousin, and two other acquaintances. He was found that evening in his pickup truck, an apparent suicide. Hunt, a convicted felon, bought his handgun online.

A 9-year-old girl survived a gunshot to call police about a shooting that left five dead at a Wade Park home. James E. Henderson was arrested six months later and charged with aggravated murder. He was convicted and sentenced to life without parole.

A 27-year-old woman, her new boyfriend, and her parents were found buried a mile from their home. Adam Matos, her former boyfriend who lived with the family, was convicted and sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole.

Police said Brandon Howell severely beat an elderly couple and fatally shot three neighbors. The couple died a week later. Howell faced a dozen charges, including three counts of first-degree murder. He was convicted and sentenced to life without parole.

Sonny Enrique Medina, 36, fatally shot his common-law wife and their three daughters, ages 10, 6 and 2, and then took his own life. The woman had talked about leaving Medina, according to a police report. She was found with numerous bruises on her arms and face.

A 22-year-old college student frustrated over sexual rejections promised in a video to "annihilate" women "on the day of retribution." Elliot Rodger, who was found dead, is suspected of the shootings that killed six and wounded seven others.

A petroleum industry engineer, his wife and two young sons were found shot in their home about a week after they were last seen alive.  Eight years later, Feng Lu, a former business associate of one of the victims, was arrested for the shootings.

Authorities have made no arrests in the case of two sisters and two men shot to death inside a home in Jacksonville's Murray Hill neighborhood. There was no sign of forced entry. Three died at the scene, while a fourth died at the hospital.

Police were called by a man saying he wanted to hurt himself. After failing to make contact with anyone inside the home, a SWAT team discovered the bodies of five victims, two of them children. Bryan E. Sweatt, 27, had committed suicide.

Charles Everett Brownlow Jr., 36, is charged with killing five people in three separate homes and a convenience store over a span of six hours. He was arrested after being chased in a vehicle and on foot. He was convicted and sentenced to death.

Michael Guzzo, 56, used a shotgun to kill the family next door -- a man, his daughter, her husband, and their son. He also killed two of their five dogs. He crossed a courtyard, fired into a unit where dogs were barking, returned home, and then killed himself.
Aaron Alexis, 34, killed 12 and injured eight in an office building at the Washington Navy Yard. The former Navy reservist was killed by police. Alexis worked for a base subcontractor.

Authorities said three teens and a young woman were shot in a car. Jacob Allen Bennett was convicted and sentenced to life without parole. His girlfriend, Brittany Moser, faced charges of felony murder and attempted robbery, and was convicted.

Samuel Sallee was found guilty of four counts of murder. The sheriff said methamphetamine was found at the rural home where a couple and two of their friends had been shot. Sallee was sentenced to life in prison.

Three neighbors who tried to intervene in a domestic dispute were killed after a gunman shot a woman inside an apartment. Dennis Clark III, the woman's live-in boyfriend, was killed by police in the complex's parking lot.

Kurt Myers, 64, shot four people, two fatally, at a barbershop In Mohawk, NY before killing two others at a car wash in the next town of Herkimer. He held police in an overnight standoff before they swarmed and killed him. Authorities do not know what provoked the attacks.

Hector Celaya was in a lengthy custody dispute involving his three children. He shot his mother, two uncles and son on the Tule Indian Reservation before fleeing with two daughters. Before he was shot by police, Celaya shot both girls, killing one.
No arrests have been made in the slayings of four people ages 16 to 34 inside a Detroit home. The day after the bodies were found, the house was torched by an arsonist and destroyed.

Four adults were shot dead in the front yard of an unlicensed boarding house in the Northridge neighborhood of Los Angeles. Ka Pasasouk, on probation at the time, was arrested the next day in Las Vegas. It is believed that he killed one of the victims as part of a robbery and then the other three to eliminate witnesses. Pasasouk was sentenced to death.

Kalcie Eagle, 21, lived a block away from the family he is accused of killing. A grandmother and three of her grandchildren were shot in their home. A 12-year-old who played dead called 911. Eagle stabbed himself to death in front of police hours later.

Officials said a financial dispute resulted in two men killing girlfriends and others connected with a drug ring associate. Zakkawanda Moss was convicted and sentenced to life in prison. Henry Lee Burrell was convicted and sentenced to life.

A 5-year-old boy escaped and told neighbors that "Daddy's dead" right after Robert Brazzon had shot his ex-brother-in-law, his wife, and their teenage son. Brazzon earlier had killed his live-in girlfriend. Brazzon shot himself after a brief standoff with police.

Dealing with a brain tumor and facing a bitter divorce, James Butwin allegedly killed his wife and three children, loaded their bodies in an SUV, took it to the desert and set it on fire. A business partner called police after finding "blood everywhere" at the family's home. Butwin committed suicide.
Ian Lee Stawicki, 40, entered a Seattle coffee shop and shot and killed four. He then killed a woman for her car, leading police on a chase that ended with Stawicki killing himself.

Nikolay Lazukin shot his wife and two daughters, suffocated his infant and set the house ablaze. He also used a baseball bat to kill a neighbor who was walking nearby. Lazukin killed himself after sending an apologetic text message to his father-in-law.

The bodies of a man, his girlfriend and two children were found naked in the woods a mile from their vehicle. Police said the killings occurred over a drug debt. James Roy Belknap received a life sentence for four counts of first-degree murder.

Tonya Thomas killed her four teenage and pre-teen children, shooting them a total of 18 times before killing herself. Three of the kids went to a neighbor's house to say their mother shot them, but Thomas called them back inside.

Jason "J.T." Ready, a well-known white supremacist who had run for public office, shot his girlfriend, three of her family members and then himself. In February, police told Ready's girlfriend to get a protective order against him; she declined.

Five men playing poker inside a Birmingham home were shot to death. Police said the slayings started as a robbery. Reginald Mims was sentenced to 25 years. Artavius Underwood and Rashad Stoves are serving life in prison.

A man facing prison described himself as despondent before he shot his girlfriend and three teenage relatives as they slept. Cedric Anderson, who a month earlier had been found guilty of heroin possession, set the house afire and then committed suicide.

A family had just finished opening Christmas presents when a relative dressed as Santa Claus opened fire, killing six before shooting himself. Azizolah "Bob" Yazdanpanah faced foreclosure and had recently separated from his wife, one of the victims.

Sara McMeen, 30, struggled with bipolar medication and postpartum depression. She shot her live-in boyfriend, two children and her 10-month-old daughter before killing herself. Forty years before, her father shot his first wife in a schizophrenic episode.

Esteban Quintero Gonzales forced his way into a trailer and shot and killed four people inside, including his two children and their mother, before killing himself. The couple had been involved in an ongoing custody dispute, sheriff's deputies said.

Jose Avila-Alva's wife refused to file domestic assault charges after an incident the week before. He opened fire on his four children in the family's front yard, killing them and committing suicide. His wife was injured but survived the shooting.

Forty hours after gaining custody of her deceased sister's three kids, Mary Ann Holder allegedly shot and killed two of them, along with two of her own and her son's girlfriend. Police said the stress of the custody case, along with an ended affair, contributed. Holder committed suicide.

Susan Hendricks received four life sentences after pleading guilty but mentally ill to the slayings of her two sons, her ex-husband, and another family member. Hendricks, who suffered from multiple mental illnesses, committed the crimes for insurance money.

David Ison will serve life in prison in the fatal shootings of five people in a rural part of Indiana. According to police reports, Ison had previously purchased drugs from one of his victims. They fought over the price of the prescription medication.

Shayne Riggleman, 22, had been diagnosed as bipolar. He killed five people -- family and friends of a couple who had taken in his ex-girlfriend. He then hit a woman with his car and shot a gas station attendant before killing himself.

Leonard Egland killed his estranged wife, her boyfriend, and the man's son. He took his own daughter, age 7, to Bucks County, PA, where he killed his mother-in-law, dropped his daughter at a hospital, wounded two policemen, and escaped. He later killed himself that night.

Using two handguns, Michael Hance went on a shooting spree, killing seven neighbors and relatives of his live-in girlfriend. His girlfriend was injured in the attack. Police fatally shot Hance outside a suburban home 10 minutes after the shooting began.

Rescue units responding to a house fire found four bodies inside. All, including two children, had been shot. Police arrested James Bannister, one victim's boyfriend, was convicted and given a life sentence.

In a protective-order affidavit, Tan Do's wife said he threatened to kill her when she tried to leave him. However, she then asked that the order be dismissed. Months later, Do shot and killed her, four of her relatives and himself at their son's birthday party.

After a lengthy mental evaluation, Everett Conant III was ruled competent. He pleaded no contest to murder in the killings of his three sons and their uncle, and one count of attempted murder in the shooting of his wife. He will serve life in prison.

Rodrick Shonte Dantzler shot himself at the end of a rampage that took the lives of seven people, including his wife, her parents, their daughter, and an ex-girlfriend. Dantzler had a history of threats against women, according to court records.

A 7-year-old girl watched as her mother was shot. She then grabbed her brother and walked four miles to a neighbor's house to call 911. Kenneth Lee Myers, 47, shot his wife (the girl's mother), two relatives, and an ex-girlfriend before he killed himself.

A pharmacy robbery ended with David Laffer shooting four people, including two store employees, before fleeing with 10,000 hydrocodone pills. His wife, a painkiller addict, drove the getaway car. Laffer received four life sentences without parole, and she received a 25-year sentence for her role.

One morning, four years after his fifth divorce, Carey Hal Dyess, 73, drove around Yuma County, shooting six people, five of them fatally: his latest ex-wife, three of her friends, and her divorce lawyer. He then pulled over and killed himself.
Gaylin Leirmoe killed his sons, their mother, and her sister at their home before setting fire to it and killing himself.

Randle Lee Roberts spared the life of an 8-year-old girl but gunned down the rest of her family, including her mother and 11-year-old sister, as they slept. Roberts fled but was killed in a shootout with police later that day.

Alan Atwater, 31, used a .22-caliber rifle to shoot his wife and three children, ages 1, 2, and 4, then himself. She had told him and her friends that she wanted to separate, according to court documents.
Three brothers and a cousin were shot on their patio while watching a Los Angeles Lakers game on TV. Police have said the shooting is gang related. It has not been solved.

An oilfield worker killed the mother of his child, then went across town to kill her brother, her mother, and her mother's boyfriend. Omar Kalmio, 27, spared his infant daughter. He will remain in prison for life without the chance for parole.

Nathan Fortner's ex-girlfriend and two of her relatives were shot dead at their home. The body of a fourth victim was found in an abandoned house where the ex-girlfriend said Fortner had sexually assaulted her just days before. Fortner committed suicide.

Police arrested Henry Segura in Minnesota 10 months after his ex-girlfriend and three children were found dead in their home.  The ex-girlfriend and one of her children  were shot at their Saddle Creek Run home. The other children were drowned and all three were left in a partially filled bathtub. Before the killings, Segura had been ordered to pay back $20,000 in child support for his son. He was convicted of murder in November 2019.

An $1,800 robbery ended in the shootings of five people, four fatally, in a home invasion in the Mattapan neighborhood. Dwayne Moore received a sentence of life in prison without parole. Kimani Washington struck a deal and got 16 to 18 years in prison.

Police came upon Patrick Dell, 32, as he shot himself on the front steps of his estranged wife's home. Inside, officers found the wife and four of her children shot dead. A fifth boy, 12, was wounded. Dell's biological children were unharmed.

When Stanley Neace's wife didn't cook his eggs the way he wanted, he became enraged and fatally shot her and her daughter, and then went to other trailer homes and shot three neighbors. Neace, 47, killed himself with a shotgun.

Lee Roy Williams told police in a recorded interview that he ''snapped'' after learning his roommates planned to evict him. He pleaded guilty to four counts of murder in the slayings of two men and two women and received four consecutive life sentences.

Police tailing suspects in a series of drug-related robberies found four men bound and shot in a garage after the suspects left. Police killed Arturo Ibarra after a chase. Raul Segura-Rodriguez faces four counts of murder in the garage shooting, but has been  convicted of a 2011 double homicide.

Brian Diez, 26, barged into his ex-girlfriend's house, shot dead five adults, and took his two young children. He brought the kids to a relative in California before committing suicide. His ex, who was killed, had a restraining order against Diez.

Ricardo M. McCray was sentenced to life without parole in a shooting outside a popular downtown bar. Four people, including a man celebrating his wedding anniversary, died. Four others were injured, one so seriously that he remains hospitalized.

Police found the bodies of two women and two children in a trash-filled garage apartment. Darrell Lynn Bellard was convicted and sentenced to life in prison without parole eligibility. Tkeisha Nicole Gilmer pleaded guilty in 2011 and was sentenced to life.

Gerardo Regalado's wife had moved out and started a new job. The couple fought in the parking lot, where he shot her, and then he ran into the restaurant where she worked, targeting women. Four died and three were injured. Regalado committed suicide.

James Larry told police he was angry his family were infidels who would not conform to his Muslim culture. He shot and killed his pregnant wife, young son and three other family members. He pleaded guilty and was imprisoned without possibility of parole.

A gathering of acquaintances at a North Hollywood Mediterranean restaurant ended when a man left and returned with a handgun, firing 50 bullets, killing four and injuring two. Nerses Galstyan was charged with four counts of murder and received a life sentence without parole eligibility.

The theft of a cheap bracelet ended in three shootings, including a drive-by that sprayed bullets at a funeral crowd, killing four teens. Jeffrey Best, Robert Bost and Orlando Carter received life without parole. Nathaniel Simms mad Lamar Williams both received prison sentences of 54 and 30 years, respectively.

Damian Jordan  had a history of violence against women, with multiple arrests for battery. He pleaded guilty to four counts of manslaughter in the shootings of his girlfriend, her sister, and her two children. Jordan was sentenced to 80 years in prison.

Two mental health evaluators found Christopher Brian Speight insane when he killed eight relatives and friends. Speight pleaded guilty to three counts of capital murder and received five life terms in prison. Police found multiple bombs at his home.

Maron Thomas spent several months at a state mental hospital after his family was found slain in their home. His 2-year-old niece had been decapitated. Thomas was later tried and convicted of murder. He was sentenced to life without parole eligibility.

On January 12, 2010, three people were killed and two others critically injured in a workplace shooting at a truck rental business located near Kennesaw, GA.  Another victim died in 2013 from complications related to his injuries. The shooter, a former employee Jesse J. Warren, was found incompetent to stand trial in 2017.

Tyrone M. Adair, 38, shot himself four days after police found his girlfriend's and infant daughter's bodies in the trunk of his car. His ex-girlfriend and a 2-year-old daughter were shot at their home. Adair was out of work and faced child support costs.

James Kraig Kahler lost his high-paying job after his domestic-assault arrest. His wife of 23 years said he was controlling. He was convicted of killing his wife, two daughters and wife's grandmother, and sentenced to death. His son, 10, was uninjured.

Paul Merhige, 35, had been treated for depression and obsessive-compulsive disorder. At Thanksgiving dinner, he shot his aunt, twin sisters and cousin and wounded two others. He pleaded guilty to avoid the death penalty and will spend life in prison.

Five adults were found dead in two trailers that had been burglarized, one was set on fire. Samuel Lee Conway was convicted in 2011, but the conviction was later overturned. In a 2016 retrial, he plead guilty to lesser charges and received a 40-year sentence for each of five murders to run concurrently.  Jeremy Pickney received 50 years for burglary charges. Marvin Stringer was killed by police.

Four people (two of whom were pregnant) were killed in a drug dispute implicating four assailants.  In exchange for a life sentence,  David Allen Tyner and Johnathan Cochran pleaded guilty and agreed to testify against Denny Phillips and Russell Hogshooter. Denny E. Phillips and Russell Hogshooter were convicted at trial and received life sentences.
